at the center of informing education policy, the contributors to this revised edition of the classic text raise tough questions that will both haunt and invigorate pre- and in-service educators, as well as veteran teachers. They explore the policies and practices of structuring exclusions; they listen hard to youth living at the margins of race, class, ethnicity, and gender; and they wrestle with fundamental inequalities of space in order to educate for change. Written from the perspective of researchers, policy analysts, teachers, and youth workers, the book reveals a shared belief in education that "could be," and a shared concern about schools that currently reproduce class, race and gender relations, and privilege.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aEducation : Multicultural Education. 4aEducation : Philosophy of Education. 4aEducation : Social Context of Education. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 a Buendia, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbrams, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbu El-Haj, Thea Renda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Janice L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Lyn Mikel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimitriadis, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElena Torre, Mariá, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFine, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFine, Michelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc